.TH _PRINTF 3 "October 2025" "Holberton School" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom implementation of the printf function
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The 
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string similar to the standard C library
.BR printf (3).
.PP
The function writes its output to the standard output (file descriptor 1)
using the
.B write(2)
system call.
.PP
Supported conversion specifiers:
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal percent sign.
.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B %i
Prints a signed decimal integer (same as %d).
.PP
Any unsupported conversion specifier will cause the function to
print the percent character
.RB (%)
followed by the unsupported character literally.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, 
.B _printf()
returns the total number of characters written.
.PP
If 
.I format
is NULL or if it contains a single percent sign with no specifier,
the function returns \-1.

.SH NOTES
This implementation is intended as an educational project and does not
support all conversion specifiers of the standard
.B printf (3)
function.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following example prints a string and an integer:
.PP
.nf
    _printf("Name: %s, Age: %d\\n", "Salman", 25);
.fi
.PP
This produces:
.PP
.nf
    Name: Salman, Age: 25
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2)

.SH AUTHOR
Written by Salman Al-Mutairi, Nizar Maharrak as part of the Holberton School C programming curriculum.
